    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-02-05T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-02-05T01:00:00-05:00" n="665"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d665">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Pacific War/1830: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Nouméa (<persName type="from"
                            >MacVitty</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nouméa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-02-05T17:00:00+11:00"
                            >February 5, 1942—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 5—2:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>17. The Australian Intelligence officer here today, informed me that a radio
                    message from the Japanese Commissioner at Hanoi to Tokyo intercepted by his
                    service reads: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Admiral Decoux<note n="54" xml:id="d665fn54">Adm. Jean Decoux, Governor
                                General of Indochina and High Commissioner for French Possessions in
                                the Pacific.</note> has agreed to cooperate with the Japanese in
                            taking possession of all French territory in the Pacific with the
                            understanding that French sovereignty will be preserved.[”]</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0681" n="675" xml:id="pg_675"/>
                <p>In this connection d’Argenlieu<note n="55" xml:id="d665fn55">Thierry d’Argenlieu,
                        Free French High Commissioner for the Pacific.</note> recently gave me to
                    understand that he believed the State Department had come to some agreement with
                    Vichy whereby no protection would be given by the United States to French
                    possessions in the Pacific. He inferred that this belief was also shared by
                    General de Gaulle.<note n="56" xml:id="d665fn56">Gen. Charles de Gaulle,
                        President of the National Committee of the Free French at London.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVitty</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
